commentText: Ex-truck driver here.   I drove Cents Per Mile, owner operator and lease operator. OTR.   It not very profitable.   -owner operator. If you buy a brand new truck, your expenses go towards the truck payment, trailer payment (which is another expense), insurance for both truck and trailer, insurance for the loads, fuel for both truck and trailer, IFTA,  Tolls (east coast tolls are absurdly expensive) . Plus,  repair schedules. Also, depends highly on what the market offers and other factors. Sure, you can earn 350k - 450k gross per year. BUT, with all of those expenses  you will net under 60k per year. And then you're taxed on personal income.  If you buy USED equipment, the same as above applies, except now there are major pending issues, repairs, and preventive  maintenance. Your equipment will become a risk factor. -Cpm (cent per mile) you can earn 50-75 cents per mile, but most  if not all, companies have you running from zipcode to zipcode basis instead of per mile. You have no control on maintenance and no control on basically anything. And then escrow gets removed, also, personal tax at 33%.  -lease operator is almost a hybrid of both owner and CPM, just depending of the clauses being signed for at the beginning of your contract agreements.  The only and best way to make good money is if you own a company and have everyone else work for you,  take no executive decisions with 200+ trucks, have your own shop, have your own insurance firm and have PRISTINE, loyal and fully dedicated drivers under your belt. But, that is just a dream.

commentText: Truck driver here. Most states have a program through the EDD to get your CLASS A CDL for free. A lot of companies will also offer to reimburse or pay for your truck school. Now that we got that out the way.  I was running local and making 100k a year cause I found a nice gig after 2 years of experience. Still with that company but now a floater (thinking about traveling nurse but as a truck driver for other local yards) and expecting to make 140k this year. I work 4 weeks and 1 week home, the one week home I still get paid. Sometimes you just gotta keep looking at the job listings other times you have to know somebody to get you in. For most local jobs though I would say expect to make around 60-80k and if hauling hazmat maybe up to 100k or decently more depending on area. Still better than a lot and more than enough to live on depending on your area.  You could also work for a mega carrier (Big Fleet companies like Swift, CR England, knight, etc.) and eventually become a trainer. I‚Äôve heard lots of numbers for this but never personally done it so can‚Äôt vouch but have heard they can make anywhere from 120-180k a year depending how many trainees they want.

commentText: During the last recession, the basic rule was take the official unemployment numbers and double them.  So when the national average was 15% unemployed, the actual number was more like 30%.  This wasn't necessarily due to malice, but at least due to artifacts and methodological issues in how the data was generated.  ADP can only see a small portion of the US job market, and while they can model outwards, their modeling has always been insufficient.  Add in the fact that there's never been a metric able to account for "underemployment," and you begin to see the real inefficiencies.  The best metric today is to consider that the historical benchmark for judging whether or not a household is "middle class," is that your yearly gross household income should be equivalent to the current market value of your home.  Take a roughly average home price of $350K, a roughly average household income of $120K, and you have your answer.
